I had an extremely disappointing experience my 1st (and last) visit to The Cecil Steakhouse  I really love a true first class steakhouse and once in a while will treat myself and go spend a bundle on a strip steak, filet mignon or rib eye, with creamed spinach  In my new neighborhood (Morningside/South Harlem) I discovered what presented as just such an establishment  I am not shy about trying new things - I went to Cecil on a week night - from the outside the place is very cool and attractive - looked to be the real deal  Interior - huge comfortable bar area - good, happy crowd - I was ushered to an absolutely beautiful, rather large deco dining room - table cloths, linen napkins - it had no patrons  The greeting I received from the waiter/host was as warm and gracious as it could possibly be - good start  I was taken aback by the prices - this is not near Rockefeller Center or the NY Stock exchange or even Peter Luger - $48 for a strip steak (24 oz - that's huge of course) - sides extra - on 118th Street and St Nicholas Avenue truly surprised me  But if I found the holy grail of steak several blocks from where I now live I am willing  I had not  My meal was shockingly disappointing - at any price - creamed spinach microwaved within an inch of its life (actually it had lost its life!) - it was a not very appealing white and gelatinous mess - no discernable taste - just a temporary minor tongue burn  But my rib eye was so tough and grissley I had real difficulty cutting with a steak knife  It was perfectly medium rare to rare, exactly as I had requested, but when I took my first bite I was overcome with an aroma that sickened me - it could only have been a swipe of butter to enhance broiling that was rancid - way too old to be used on any broiled food, much less a $44 rib eye steak  So I struggled to eat (no reason to send it back and be confronted with another disappointment) because I went in starving - it was an expensive experiment - this was a very worthwhile gamble but I lost my chips  It's sad that such a beautiful, appealing restaurant space, a great asset to a burgeoning neighborhood, had no idea how poor the quality of the food is  Get a chef who knows how to broil a steak and wouldn't dream of buying meat that the chain Tad's would not have served  I remain hopeful
